Hyundai Heavy, Hyundai Motor, SK: South Korea Stocks Preview

-- B y   S a e r o m i   S h i n
-- 
2011-06-08T23:33:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-08/hyundai-heavy-hyundai-motor-sk-south-korea-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies may
have unusual moves in  South Korea  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The  Kospi Index (KOSPI)  fell 16.36, or 0.8 percent, to 2,083.35.
Equity and index options and equity and index futures contracts
expire today, a event known as quadruple witching. Stock markets
are often volatile on the expiration day because of a pickup in
 program trading .  Airlines and refiners: Oil rose to a one-week high in  New
York  after OPEC failed to reach an agreement on production
targets for the first time in at least 20 years at its meeting
in Vienna. SK Innovation Co. (096770 KS) rose 2.1 percent to
224,000 won.  GS Holdings (078930)  Corp. (078930 KS) added 2.6 percent to
84,600 won. Korean Air Lines Co. (003490 KS) climbed 1.6 percent
to 63,800 won.  Hyundai Heavy Industries Co. (009540 KS): Creditors of
 Hynix Semiconductor Inc. (000660)  (000660 KS) suggested that Hyundai
Heavy Industries and Hyundai Motor Group form a group in making
a bid for a planned stake sale, MoneyToday said, without citing
anyone. Hyundai Heavy sank 5.6 percent to 466,000 won.  Hyundai
Motor Co. (005380)  (005380 KS) retreated 2.7 percent to 231,500 won.
Hynix gained 1.1 percent to 28,900 won.  Posco (005490)  (005490 KS): South Korea’s biggest steelmaker will
purchase a 20 percent stake in XG Sciences Inc., a U.S. graphene
maker, according to a statement that didn’t give an investment
value. The stock rose 0.1 percent to 433,000 won.  Samsung Electronics Co. (005930 KS): Samsung began to
produce large-scale integration, or LSI, chips used in mobile
devices at its Austin, Texas plant last month, Jason Kim, a
company spokesman said.  Asia ’s biggest maker of chips, flat
screens and mobile phones lost 1.1 percent to 877,000 won.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Saeromi Shin in Seoul at 
